default3.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs early as 1992, among others Pometto et al. published a scientific study of the possibility of the biodegradation of polyethylene by means of enzymes. Sc
defaulti
defaultentists agree that enzymes are present in soil, which can decompose polyethy
defaultl
defaultene. However, so far these enzymes could not be identified and also their exact function is not fully understood. Above all it was never possible, despite years of research, to influence the speed of the decomposition.
default The scientists at AESL have now discovered the mechanics of these enzymatic reactions in polyolefin. 
default3.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe solution is not just a single enzyme, but six specific ones out of about 250 thousand different types of enzymes, so-called Multienzymecomplexes, which interact or co-operate with each other to regulate themselves. 
defaultReverse engineering in this case is almost impossible. The Multienzymeco
defaultm
defaultplex is “encapsulated” into LLDPE, which serves as a carrier for the further processing of polyethylene products.
default3.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPolyethylene is difficult to biodegrade mainly due to its high molecular weight and the non-polar C-C and C-H bonds. Furthermore the macromolecular pol
defaulty
defaultmer chains have a very dense branch, which results in a low total surface area. Thus, no water or oxygen can normally penetrate into the interior of the basic material. In addition, antioxidants may be added during the manufacturing pro
defaultc
defaultess to prevent an oxygenation reaction.
default 
default3.7
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOnce the enzymes are activated in the polyethylene, the biological degradation starts at the weakest link in the polymer chain. Thus, the molecular mass is r
defaulte
defaultduced and other microorganisms and fungi can start to decompose the modified polyethylene. The incorporated enzymes promote the growth of the correspon
defaultd
defaulting organisms and cultures, which further accelerate the process until all pol
defaulty
defaultethylene chains are divided into the original substances, Carbon and Hydrogen and then CO
default2
default and water are produced. The aforementioned process is only a
defaultc
defaulttivated under certain environmental conditions. This prevents premature biode
defaultg
defaultradation, thus allowing the reuse of the product. Listed below are the required criteria similar to any compost or biodegradation process:
default3.8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultShould any one of these parameters be lacking, the process is not initiated and the polyethylene retains its usual properties. The number of microorganisms on the hands, shelf or in a warehouse is not enough to initiate the process.
